            <section class="card" data-aos="fade-right" id="22">
                <img src="Images/9e20bac3-f367-4b8d-be23-25ac5ad8d1d6.jpg" alt="acne skin">   
                <div>
                    <h3>About acne Skin</h3>

    <p>
       Pimples and acne are very common skin problems that affect people of all ages, especially teenagers and young adults. Although many people use the words pimple and acne as the same, they are slightly different. A pimple is a small bump or spot on the skin, while acne is a skin condition that causes repeated pimples, blackheads, whiteheads, and sometimes painful cysts.
        <span id="dots3">...</span>
        
        <span id="more3" class="more-text" style="display:none;">
           Pimples and acne usually appear on the face, forehead, cheeks, chin, back, and shoulders. The main reason behind pimples and acne is clogged pores. When the skin produces too much oil (sebum), it mixes with dead skin cells and dirt, blocking the pores. This blockage allows bacteria to grow, which leads to swelling, redness, and breakouts. Hormonal changes, stress, unhealthy diet, lack of hygiene, and using wrong skincare products can also increase acne. The good thing is that pimples and acne can be controlled naturally at home, and for severe cases dermatology provides effective and long-term solutions. To tackle pimples and acne naturally, the first step is proper cleansing. Washing the face twice a day with a gentle cleanser removes excess oil, dust, and bacteria. It is important not to wash the face too many times because over-washing can make the skin dry and irritated, which can lead to more oil production and more pimples. Another important habit is avoiding touching the face frequently. Hands carry germs and bacteria that can transfer to the skin and worsen acne. Popping or squeezing pimples is also a major mistake because it can cause infections, scars, and dark spots. One of the best natural remedies for pimples and acne is aloe vera gel. Aloe vera has antibacterial and anti-inflammatory properties that help reduce redness, swelling, and irritation. Applying fresh aloe vera gel daily on acne-prone skin can calm breakouts and speed up healing. Tea tree oil is another powerful natural remedy because it kills acne-causing bacteria. However, tea tree oil should always be diluted with a carrier oil like coconut oil or mixed with water before applying, because using it directly may cause skin burning or dryness. Honey is also very helpful because it is naturally antibacterial and keeps skin moisturized. Applying honey on pimples for 10 to 15 minutes can reduce inflammation and prevent bacterial growth. Turmeric is another natural ingredient used widely for acne because it reduces bacteria and swelling. A turmeric mask mixed with yogurt or honey can help clear acne, but it should be used carefully because turmeric may leave yellow stains on the skin temporarily. Ice cubes can also help reduce swelling and redness quickly. Applying ice on a painful pimple for a few minutes gives relief and decreases inflammation. Besides home remedies, lifestyle changes are extremely important for controlling pimples and acne. Drinking enough water daily keeps the skin hydrated and helps remove toxins from the body. A healthy diet plays a major role in preventing breakouts. Eating too much oily fast food, sugary snacks, and junk food can increase acne because these foods raise hormones and oil production. Instead, eating fruits, vegetables, and foods rich in omega-3 fatty acids like fish, walnuts, and flax seeds helps reduce inflammation and improves skin health. Zinc-rich foods like pumpkin seeds, lentils, and chickpeas are also beneficial because zinc reduces acne and supports immune function. Some people notice more pimples after consuming dairy products like milk, so reducing dairy can help if it triggers acne. Stress is another major cause of acne because stress increases cortisol hormones, which leads to more oil production and breakouts. Getting good sleep, exercising daily, and practicing relaxation methods like meditation can reduce stress and improve skin condition. Hygiene is also very important in acne control. Pillow covers, towels, and bedsheets should be washed regularly because they collect oil and bacteria that can transfer to the face. Hair should also be kept clean because oily hair and hair products can clog pores when they touch the skin. Using non-comedogenic skincare and makeup products is also important because these products do not block pores. Removing makeup before sleeping is necessary because makeup left overnight can worsen acne. Natural masks like multani mitti (fuller’s earth) mixed with rose water can reduce excess oil and unclog pores, making it a good remedy for oily acne-prone skin. Green tea is also useful because it contains antioxidants that fight inflammation. Drinking green tea or applying cooled green tea as a toner can help reduce acne. While natural remedies and healthy habits can work well for mild acne, dermatology treatment is required when acne becomes severe, painful, or long-lasting. Dermatologists explain that acne may be caused by hormones, genetics, or skin conditions, and in such cases professional treatment is needed. Dermatology treatments include topical creams and gels such as benzoyl peroxide, salicylic acid, and retinoids. Benzoyl peroxide kills acne bacteria and reduces swelling, salicylic acid removes dead skin cells and clears pores, and retinoids prevent clogged pores and reduce future breakouts. If acne is moderate to severe, dermatologists may prescribe oral antibiotics to reduce infection and inflammation. For hormonal acne, especially in females, doctors may recommend hormonal therapy such as birth control pills or anti-androgen medicines. In very severe cases, isotretinoin is prescribed. This is a strong medicine that reduces oil production and can clear acne permanently for many people, but it must be taken under strict medical supervision because it may cause side effects. Dermatologists also offer advanced treatments like chemical peels, laser therapy, and microdermabrasion to treat acne and reduce scars. Chemical peels remove dead skin layers and reduce oiliness, while laser therapy targets acne bacteria and improves skin texture. Dermatologists also emphasize the importance of using moisturizer and sunscreen. Many people think acne skin does not need moisturizer, but in reality a light oil-free moisturizer helps maintain skin balance. Sunscreen is important because acne treatments make skin sensitive and sunlight can worsen dark spots and acne scars. In conclusion, pimples and acne can be tackled naturally by keeping the skin clean, avoiding touching the face, using aloe vera, honey, turmeric, and tea tree oil, drinking water, eating healthy food, reducing stress, and maintaining good hygiene. For severe acne, dermatology treatments such as medicated creams, oral medicines, and professional procedures provide faster and long-lasting results. The best way to get clear skin is consistency and patience because acne takes time to heal. By combining natural care and dermatology advice, anyone can achieve healthy, smooth, and glowing skin.
        </span>
    </p>

