    <section class="card" data-aos="fade-left">
                <img src="Images/Blog-Dark_Circles_Header-01.jpg" alt="Dark circles">   
                <div>
                    <h3>About dark circles</h3>
                    

    <p>
        Dark circles under the eyes are a very common skin problem faced by many people of all ages. They usually appear as dark, dull, or shadowy patches under the eyes and can make the face look tired, older, and unhealthy. Dark circles are not always a serious medical issue, but they can affect confidence and overall appearance. There are many reasons why dark circles develop.
        <span id="dots4">...</span>
        
        <span id="more4" class="more-text" style="display:none;">
            One of the most common causes is lack of sleep. When a person does not get enough rest, the skin becomes pale and dull, and the blood vessels under the eyes become more visible, creating a dark appearance. Stress and mental tension can also worsen dark circles because stress affects blood circulation and skin health. Another major cause is dehydration. When the body does not have enough water, the skin becomes dry and weak, and the area under the eyes starts looking darker. Genetics also play an important role. Some people naturally have dark circles because it runs in their family. In such cases, dark circles may not fully disappear, but they can be reduced with proper care. Excessive screen time is another reason for dark circles. When we use mobile phones, laptops, or computers for long hours, our eyes become tired and strained, which can lead to dark circles. Allergies are also a common cause because rubbing the eyes repeatedly due to itching can damage the sensitive skin and make it darker. Aging is another natural reason because as we grow older, the skin becomes thinner and loses collagen, making the blood vessels under the eyes more noticeable. Poor diet and lack of vitamins can also cause dark circles. If a person is not eating enough healthy food, especially iron, vitamin C, and vitamin K, the skin under the eyes can become dark and weak. To handle dark circles effectively, the first step is improving lifestyle habits. Getting enough sleep is the most important solution. Adults should sleep at least 7 to 8 hours daily because proper sleep repairs skin and reduces tiredness. Drinking enough water is also necessary because hydration keeps the skin fresh and prevents dryness. A healthy diet is another key factor. Eating fruits and vegetables rich in vitamins helps improve blood circulation and skin glow. Foods like oranges, lemons, carrots, spinach, and tomatoes provide vitamin C and antioxidants that reduce pigmentation. Iron-rich foods like eggs, meat, lentils, and spinach help reduce dark circles caused by anemia. Reducing salt intake is also important because too much salt causes water retention and puffiness under the eyes, making dark circles look worse. One of the best home remedies for dark circles is applying cold compress. You can use ice cubes wrapped in cloth or cold spoons and place them under the eyes for a few minutes. This helps shrink blood vessels and reduces darkness. Cucumber slices are also a popular remedy because cucumber has cooling properties and natural antioxidants that soothe the skin. Placing cucumber slices on the eyes for 10 to 15 minutes daily can reduce puffiness and lighten dark circles. Potato juice is another effective remedy because it contains natural bleaching agents. Applying potato juice under the eyes for 10 minutes can improve skin brightness. Aloe vera gel is also very helpful because it hydrates the skin and reduces pigmentation. Applying aloe vera under the eyes daily can make the skin smoother and fresher. Another useful remedy is almond oil. Almond oil is rich in vitamin E, which nourishes the skin and helps lighten dark circles over time. Gently massaging a few drops of almond oil under the eyes before sleeping can show good results. Tea bags, especially green tea or black tea, are also beneficial. Used tea bags kept in the fridge and placed under the eyes help reduce swelling and improve dark circles because tea contains caffeine and antioxidants. Along with these remedies, it is important to stop rubbing the eyes because rubbing can damage the thin skin and worsen the dark color. Using sunscreen is also important because sun exposure increases pigmentation and makes dark circles darker. A good under-eye cream with ingredients like vitamin C, hyaluronic acid, retinol, or caffeine can also help reduce dark circles. In severe cases, dermatologists may recommend treatments like chemical peels, laser therapy, or fillers. These treatments improve skin texture and reduce pigmentation. In conclusion, dark circles can be handled by improving sleep, drinking water, eating healthy food, reducing stress, and using natural remedies like cucumber, potato juice, almond oil, aloe vera, and cold compress. With regular care and patience, dark circles can be reduced and the face can look fresh, healthy, and bright.
        </span>
    </p>

