            <section class="card" data-aos="fade-left">
                <img src="Images/applying-moisturizer-lede.webp"alt="Moisturize skin">   
                <div>
                    <h3>About moisturize skin</h3>

    <p>
        Choosing the right moisturizer for your skin type is an essential step in maintaining healthy, hydrated, and glowing skin, yet many people struggle to select the product that suits their individual needs. Moisturizers are designed to lock in moisture, protect the skin barrier, and improve texture, but selecting the wrong type can lead to dryness, oiliness, or even breakouts.
        
        <span id="dots6">...</span>
        
        <span id="more6" class="more-text" style="display:none;">
            The first step in choosing a moisturizer is identifying your skin type, which generally falls into four categories: dry, oily, combination, and sensitive. Dry skin feels tight, rough, or flaky, and often lacks natural oils, so people with dry skin should opt for rich, cream-based moisturizers that contain ingredients like hyaluronic acid, glycerin, shea butter, or ceramides, which deeply hydrate and restore the skin barrier. Oily skin, on the other hand, produces excess sebum and is prone to acne, so lightweight, oil-free, or gel-based moisturizers are ideal because they provide hydration without clogging pores or adding extra oil. Ingredients like niacinamide, aloe vera, or hyaluronic acid work well for oily skin by balancing oil production while keeping the skin soft. Combination skin has both dry and oily areas, usually with an oily T-zone (forehead, nose, and chin) and drier cheeks, so those with combination skin should use a moisturizer that is lightweight, non-greasy, and suitable for all areas, or even consider using two different moisturizers for different zones. Sensitive skin is easily irritated, prone to redness or itching, and reacts strongly to harsh chemicals, fragrances, or alcohol-based products, so it is important to choose a gentle, hypoallergenic moisturizer with calming ingredients such as aloe vera, chamomile, or oat extract. Beyond skin type, climate and season also influence the choice of moisturizer; for example, in hot and humid weather, lighter formulations like gels or lotions are preferable, while in cold and dry climates, richer creams or ointments provide better protection and hydration. It is also essential to consider the active ingredients in moisturizers. Humectants like hyaluronic acid and glycerin attract water to the skin, emollients like shea butter and squalene smooth and soften the skin, and occlusives like petrolatum or dimethicone create a protective barrier to prevent water loss. People should also be aware of non-comedogenic labels if they are prone to acne, as these products are formulated to avoid clogging pores. Patch testing a new moisturizer before applying it to the entire face is a wise step to ensure no allergic reaction or irritation occurs. Additionally, layering moisturizers over serums or treatments can enhance hydration and skin benefits, but it is important to follow the correct order—lightweight serums first, then moisturizer. Dermatologists often recommend adjusting your moisturizer as your skin changes over time due to age, hormonal changes, or lifestyle factors, emphasizing that there is no one-size-fits-all solution. In conclusion, choosing the right moisturizer requires understanding your skin type, evaluating ingredients, considering environmental factors, and observing how your skin responds. By selecting a moisturizer that meets your skin’s unique needs, you can maintain hydration, protect the skin barrier, and achieve healthy, radiant skin that feels comfortable and looks naturally glowing.
        </span>
    </p>

